g on cutting-edge insights from the fields of political science, philosophy, and law. Nine timely essays explore our pivotal moment in history, from the question of reparations for slavery to the from the art—and impact—of the public apology.The editors of this volume encourage us to not only examine the roots of mistrust, but also to imagine a collective way forward, particularly as we face the continuing threat of the COVID-19 pandemic. Reconciliation and Repair provides thought-provoking perspectives in an age where they are desperately needed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReconciliationxPolitical aspects. 0aReparations for historical injusticesvCongresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aalienation.  aapologies.  aatonement model.  acolonialism.  acritical race theory.  apublic apologies.  aracial injustice.  areconciliation.  arepair.  areparations.  aslavery.  astructural injustice.1 aBeerbohm, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeerbohm, Eric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrooks, Roy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendrix, Burke A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJagmohan, Desmond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinow, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMohamed, Saira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Colleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreston-Roedder, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadzik, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.